04203nam a22005415i 9780822380726DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20002000ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223807267 a10.1515/97808223807262doi  a(DE-B1597)553243  a(OCoLC)1055289511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPQ7082.N7bP75 2000 7aLIT0040502bisacsh04a8632211 aPrieto, René, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBody of Writing :bFiguring Desire in Spanish American Literature /cRené Prieto. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (308 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Julio Cortázar's perpetual exile -- t2 More than meets the I: Guillermo Cabrera Infante's -- t3 The excremental vision of Gabriel García Márquez -- t4 The degraded body in the work of Severo Sarduy -- t5 Rewriting the body: renewal through language in the work of Rosario Castellanos -- t6 The body of pleasure in Tununa Mercado's -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBody of Writing focuses on the traces that an author's "body" leaves on a work of fiction. Drawing on the work of six important Spanish American writers of the twentieth century, René Prieto examines narratives that reflect-in differing yet ultimately complementary ways-the imprint of the author's body, thereby disclosing insights about power, aggression, transgression, and eroticism.Healthy, invalid, lustful, and confined bodies-as portrayed by Julio Cortázar, Guillermo Cabrera Infante, Gabriel García Márquez, Severo Sarduy, Rosario Castellanos, and Tununa Mercado-become evidence for Roland Barthes's contention that works of fiction are "anagrams of the body." Claiming that an author's intentions can be uncovered by analyzing "the topography of a text," Prieto pays particular attention not to the actions or plots of these writers' fiction but rather to their settings and characterizations. In the belief that bodily traces left on the page reveal the motivating force behind a writer's creative act, he explores such fictional themes as camouflage, deterioration, defilement, entrapment, and subordination. Along the way, Prieto reaches unexpected conclusions regarding topics that include the relationship of the female body to power, male and female transgressive impulses, and the connection between aggression, the idealization of women, and anal eroticism in men.This study of how authors' longings and fears become embodied in literature will interest students and scholars of literary and psychoanalytic criticism, gender studies, and twentieth-century and Latin American literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aSex role in literature. 0aSpanish American fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822380726zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822380726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822380726.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles